  "doc_id": "41003",
  "text": "Of major importance for the characterization of gene regulatory network models is the identification of the network structure. Various enhancer or repressor binding sites may be present in the promoter region of a gene. The identification of binding sites using for example ChIP-seq data involves a sequence of classical bioinformatics applications [CITATION_1] . The reads identified by ChIP-seq yield a fuzzy picture of counts over base pair position, from which peaks are selected in a sophisticated procedure named \"peak calling\" and used as a source to search for overrepresented sequence motifs [CITATION_2] . Motifs, such as the E-, D-boxes and RREs, known binding sites for core-clock genes, can be represented as a simple sequence or position weight matrix (PWM). The matrix can subsequently be matched to positions in the genome considering the statistics of random occurrences and associated to promoter regions of specific clock-target genes [CITATION_3] .",
